Sure. So we have a question from Bill with asterisks, so I will ask it. And it is,

00:14:36.119 --> 00:14:42.280
what were the pluses and minuses, sort of a comparison of moving from R to Python? Like,

00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:46.919
were you dragged into this transition or were you OK with it and onboard? How did it go?

00:14:47.559 --> 00:14:52.840
Sure. No, that's a great question. And, you know, that's an interesting question because

00:14:53.479 --> 00:14:59.080
I professionally do a lot mostly in Python programming, but I still have this R package

00:14:59.799 --> 00:15:05.320
that I'm maintaining. So, you know, kind of personally on the side, nights and weekends,

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:15.000
chipping away at that package as well. And I think to be honest, a lot of what I'm doing is

00:15:16.119 --> 00:15:20.359
getting questions from the portfolio management team or other teams.

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:24.280
And we ideally want to be able to use the systems that we have in place

00:15:25.640 --> 00:15:30.280
to answer their question. And to be honest, they just have a question they want to answer. They

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:34.919
don't necessarily need to know how you're coming up or which tools you're using to answer that

00:15:34.919 --> 00:15:40.440
question. It's more fast paced in that sense. So really, whatever it is that gets the job done

00:15:40.440 --> 00:15:47.320
the fastest is really all that matters. But if the system can't handle it, you're on your own.

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:52.919
And that's really where the quantitative skills come into play. And R and Python, in my opinion,

00:15:52.919 --> 00:15:57.559
are so similar. And I've heard it mentioned a few times that maybe there's the whole tension

00:15:57.559 --> 00:16:02.679
because they are so similar and people are comparing them because of that. If they were

00:16:02.679 --> 00:16:09.000
so different or special from each other, then they wouldn't have those conversations. It'd be obvious

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:14.359
which way to go, but it's maybe not. And that's why. So in my mind, I think they're so similar,

00:16:14.359 --> 00:16:21.320
there's really not much differentiation. And I've been a pretty big adopter myself of doing

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:30.840
a lot of stats in R or in Python, and then doing a lot of the graphing in R with ggplot as well.

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:38.760
So I've been a pretty big adopter of the Quarto framework more recently. And I've been using

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:45.479
RStudio for a very long time, actually. I remember hearing about it way back in 2011

00:16:45.479 --> 00:16:51.159
when it was presented at R and Finance. So it's been good to see it evolve over the years to

00:16:51.159 --> 00:16:58.119
really support the two languages, R and Python, especially. And then Ozzatron this year has been

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:06.040
nice to see as well and excited for what comes there as well. But regardless, if your whole

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:14.760
firm switches over to Python, for me personally, it was not hard. Like I said, I think R and Python

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:21.640
are so easy in terms of transitioning and answering very similar questions with both.

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:28.439
And you have to keep in mind, though, one thing is who is going to support the system in place

00:17:28.439 --> 00:17:35.959
at your firm. So if all of the technology teams know Python and they don't know R,

00:17:36.920 --> 00:17:41.239
and you want to ask them a R question, it's going to be very challenging to get much

00:17:41.239 --> 00:17:48.359
out of them or support or traction on your problem that you're facing. And really,

00:17:48.359 --> 00:17:53.880
if you're trying to get your job done, you want to just do what is maybe easier and more seamless

00:17:53.880 --> 00:18:00.040
to do. And that's one of the selling points of switching to something that's well supported

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:06.599
within your firm, whether it's R or in Python as well. So you go to both, but you also want to be

00:18:06.599 --> 00:18:13.640
able to have impact on your job and you want to get the job done. And if your whole technology

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:20.439
team knows Python, then it's a lot easier to speak the same language and to really have that support

00:18:20.439 --> 00:18:27.000
from them as well. And it's not so much of an uphill battle to get what you might need out of

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:33.079
them or to do your job within the day. So hopefully that answers your question. It's definitely a good

00:18:33.079 --> 00:18:39.800
one. And I think for me personally, it goes back to moving around a lot as a kid and just being

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:48.520
in different environments. You just kind of have to adapt and try to use what's in your environment

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:51.000
to your benefit as much as possible.

