switching from MATLAB into Python and a bunch of folks just skipping the whole R element entirely,

00:19:41.719 --> 00:19:49.800
which was interesting to me. And in terms of training, one thing that I did initially was

00:19:50.359 --> 00:19:57.000
set up some exercises for people. So, putting together, you want to use formats that are

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:05.719
similar to what people would use internally. So, creating a PowerPoint deck that is going

00:20:05.719 --> 00:20:12.359
through exercises that you would normally need to do for your day job and asking questions along

00:20:12.359 --> 00:20:18.599
the way. So, for example, in the risk world, you can think of, in terms of risk, a lot of people

00:20:18.599 --> 00:20:23.319
would think about volatility and standard deviations. So, if you wanted to calculate a

00:20:23.319 --> 00:20:28.760
standard deviation of a return series, how would you do that in Python and going through the simple

00:20:28.760 --> 00:20:34.520
example there? And then your firm might have some custom tweaks to how they calculate that. So,

00:20:34.520 --> 00:20:39.239
how would you do that and how would you maybe tap into these APIs that you would use internally?

00:20:40.280 --> 00:20:45.800
You think of it like asking a question and you have some questions and you take out the

00:20:45.800 --> 00:20:51.400
answers a little bit and you make them do and solve some of the problems themselves by using

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:58.119
Python or whatever language and to really show them what they need to do to get their day job

00:20:58.119 --> 00:21:03.719
and to make it have a bigger impact on what they need to do. So, it kind of motivates people when

00:21:03.719 --> 00:21:11.160
