teams that have poor working relationships? Yeah, that's a good one. That's an unavoidable

00:42:48.360 --> 00:42:55.000
situation there, too. So it definitely depends on the different types of different types of

00:42:55.000 --> 00:43:03.399
teams and the different types of people on those teams. And, you know, in the different domains,

00:43:03.399 --> 00:43:10.280
you can have different types of personalities. And, you know, it really goes to how you can kind

00:43:10.280 --> 00:43:17.959
of navigate that domain is pretty challenging. So, you know, one thing that I've noticed over the

00:43:17.959 --> 00:43:28.120
years is I like to be just as passionate about my work as maybe other people would do their job.

00:43:28.120 --> 00:43:34.840
So if you can try to be more partner-like with them and really show them, try to put

00:43:34.840 --> 00:43:40.439
yourselves in their shoes is another way, I guess, of thinking about it. So if you think about, okay,

00:43:40.439 --> 00:43:45.320
if I was some person who just got this email request from this person, this other team,

00:43:45.879 --> 00:43:52.760
you know, what does it mean? Why should I care about it? And they might have a pretty negative

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:57.320
response to you off the bat. But if you can kind of put yourselves into their shoes, maybe you

00:43:57.320 --> 00:44:04.679
could reframe that email or that ask in a way to really get a better outcome. And that's something

00:44:04.679 --> 00:44:10.120
that is challenging to do. So think about it from the other person's perspective. But that's something

00:44:10.120 --> 00:44:17.159
that I find works pretty well too. So it's unavoidable for conflicts, but really to understand

00:44:18.199 --> 00:44:22.520
where it is that they're coming from. And you can kind of draw parallels in a way to,

00:44:23.159 --> 00:44:27.560
you know, I don't want to open up a whole can of worms here, but, you know, open source development,

00:44:28.280 --> 00:44:34.840
you know, you can get, I think of it like anybody today or tomorrow can go open up an issue request

00:44:34.840 --> 00:44:40.199
on my GitHub and write whatever they want on it. And maybe it makes me feel great, or maybe it

00:44:40.199 --> 00:44:45.639
doesn't. You know, I really shouldn't try to take it personally. Anyone can do what they want. But

00:44:46.199 --> 00:44:49.479
trying to then take a step back and to really think about it from their

00:44:50.760 --> 00:44:56.600
perspective and maybe reframing the question in a way that's better and maybe leads to a

00:44:56.600 --> 00:45:02.199
better outcome would be a better scenario for everyone. And I've said this a few times, but

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:08.919
maybe even reframing into a way of they're asking a question and you could be getting a better

00:45:08.919 --> 00:45:14.919
outcome if they've asked a slightly different question. And that leads to a better outcome

00:45:14.919 --> 00:45:20.040
for everyone. And then maybe even you are motivated to tackle the problem, even though it came off

00:45:20.040 --> 00:45:27.159
very negative at the beginning there too. So I like to think of it, I guess, from a different

00:45:27.159 --> 00:45:33.399
person's perspective. And they can ask anything at any time. And you want to keep an open mind

00:45:33.399 --> 00:45:39.639
and maybe just take a deep breath, take a step back and to think about how can you solve the

00:45:39.639 --> 00:45:44.840
problem more generally than maybe what they're asking in a very narrow sense at the same time too.

